---
import AboutHeroImage from '../assets/blog-placeholder-about.jpg';
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About Me"
	description="Lead Data Scientist. I build analyses for sticky, info-scarce problems."
	pubDate={new Date('May 03 2026')}
	heroImage={AboutHeroImage}
	curlicueIntensity="soft"
>
	<p>
		I'm a Lead Data Scientist. Most of my career has been in the analytics and ML layer of consumer
		tech: supply economics, experimentation design, clustering, data governance, that kind of work.
		I've built things that got productized and things that got ignored, and I've learned more from
		the second category.
	</p>

	<p>
		This blog is for problems I find sticky. The common thread: the data exists, it just hasn't been
		assembled in a way that's useful yet. Before I start any analysis, I ask what decision it
		unlocks. If the answer is "nothing changes regardless of what we find," I usually don't do the
		analysis. The posts here passed that test, at least in my own estimation.
	</p>

	<p>
		So far that has meant: counting how many unique Magic: The Gathering cards exist and how the
		supply has changed over 30 years; building a text-derived efficiency score for all 27,000 of
		them; checking that score against what competitive Legacy players actually register; and using
		linear programming to figure out which regions of Skyrim are worth your foraging time given a
		specific character build. These are not the same domain. That's the point. The methodology
		travels; the subject matter is whatever I'm curious about.
	</p>

	<p>
		My brother reintroduced me to Magic during COVID, which is either a gift or a curse depending on
		how you look at my discretionary spending since 2020. He also beats me regularly, which is part
		of why I started building models instead of improving my actual play.
	</p>

	<p>
		If something here is wrong or interesting, I'd genuinely like to know.
		The code for every post is in the <a href="https://github.com/ckeneha1/gatheringdata-blog">GitHub repo</a>.
	</p>
</Layout>
